HASHING (PRESTORE/FETCHING)
What is Hashing?
One-line definition

Hashing is a technique for storing information so that it can be searched extremely quickly.

Hashing is used to store and retrieve data efficiently.
 Instead of searching the entire array every time (O(n)), 
we preprocess the data once and then answer queries in O(1) average time using a hash table. 
This avoids repeatedly traversing the array.




Hashing

Stored useful information.

Example:

Number -> Frequency

Character -> Frequency

Number -> Index

Reason:

Avoid searching again.


Prefix Sum

Stored:

Prefix Sum

Reason:

Avoid recalculating subarray sums.

Sliding Window

Stores:

Current Window

Reason:

Avoid recalculating overlapping elements.

Notice something?

Every topic is about not repeating work.

Topic	What is reused?
Hashing	Previous information
Prefix Sum	Previous cumulative sum
Sliding Window	Previous window

This is why I wanted to compare topics—you start seeing the underlying idea instead of memorizing techniques.



Without hashing:
Query
↓
Search entire array
↓
O(n)

With hashing:
Preprocess once
↓
Store frequencies/values
↓
Direct lookup
↓
O(1) average

