Why unordered_set instead of set?

A good answer is:

We don't need the elements in sorted order.
 We only need fast lookup to check whether an element 
 has already been seen.
 unordered_set provides O(1) average insertion and lookup,
 while set takes O(log n), so unordered_set is a better fit.



  THINK IN THIS WAY:
 | Requirement         | Data Structure                    |
| ------------------- | --------------------------------- |
| Need sorted order   | `set` / `map`                     |
| Need fastest lookup | `unordered_set` / `unordered_map` |
| Need frequency      | `unordered_map`                   |
| Need only existence | `unordered_set`          


 🧠 Golden Rule

Whenever you see:

unordered_map<A,B>

Ask yourself:

What should my key represent?

What should my value represent?   

 Question:
Need Frequency?
→ unordered_map<value, frequency>

Need Index?
→ unordered_map<value, index>

Need Existence?
→ unordered_set

Need Sorted?
→ map / set    |


two sum:
If I were interviewing you, I'd ask:

Why didn't you sort the array?

Expected answer:

Because sorting changes the original indices. The problem asks us to return the original indices, so hashing is a better fit.

Need frequency?
↓
unordered_map


Need existence?
↓
unordered_set

Need sorted?
↓

map/set


arr.find(boom)!=arr.end();

find(key)
    ↓
Checks existence only
(Never changes the map)

mpp[key]
    ↓
Accesses the value
If the key doesn't exist,
it creates a new entry.



